@label ADSCFT
    \textbf{The Central Dictionary}

    The fundamental statement of AdS/CFT is an equality between two partition
    functions:

    $$Z_\text{string}[\phi_0] = Z_\text{CFT}[\phi_0] \tag{0}$$

    where $\phi_0$ is a field configuration defined on the boundary. Everything
    else flows from unpacking what each side means.

    \textbf{The Gravity Side}

    The bulk spacetime is $(d+1)$-dimensional Anti-de Sitter space,
    $\text{AdS}_{d+1}$. Its metric in Poincaré coordinates is:

    $$ds^2 = \frac{L^2}{z^2}\left(-dt^2 + d\vec{x}^2 + dz^2\right) \tag{1}$$

    where $L$ is the AdS radius and $z > 0$ is the radial coordinate. The
    boundary sits at $z \to 0$; the deep interior at $z \to \infty$.

    The bulk action is Einstein gravity with a negative cosmological constant:

    $$S_\text{bulk} = \frac{1}{16\pi G_N} \int d^{d+1}x\,\sqrt{-g}
    \left(R + \frac{d(d-1)}{L^2}\right) + S_\text{matter} \tag{2}$$

    A bulk field $\phi(x, z)$ of mass $m$ satisfies the Klein-Gordon equation:

    $$\left(\Box_\text{AdS} - m^2\right)\phi = 0 \tag{3}$$

    Near $z \to 0$ this has two independent solutions:

    $$\phi(x, z) \;\sim\; z^{d-\Delta}\,\phi_0(x) \;+\; z^{\Delta}\,
    \langle O(x)\rangle \;+\; \cdots \tag{4}$$

    where $\Delta$ is the conformal dimension, related to the bulk mass by:

    $$\Delta = \frac{d}{2} + \sqrt{\frac{d^2}{4} + m^2 L^2} \tag{5}$$

    The leading term $\phi_0(x)$ is the boundary value freely specified as a
    source; the subleading term $\langle O(x)\rangle$ is the response, determined
    dynamically. The bulk partition function in the saddle-point approximation is:

    $$Z_\text{grav}[\phi_0] = e^{-S_\text{on-shell}[\phi_0]} \tag{6}$$

    \textbf{The CFT Side}

    On the boundary lives a Conformal Field Theory invariant under $SO(d,2)$ —
    the same as the isometry group of $\text{AdS}_{d+1}$: the first deep
    structural match.

    The CFT partition function with source $\phi_0$ coupled to operator $O$ is:

    $$Z_\text{CFT}[\phi_0] = \left\langle \exp\!\left(
    \int d^d x\,\phi_0(x)\,O(x)\right)\right\rangle_{\!\text{CFT}} \tag{7}$$

    Differentiating with respect to $\phi_0$ extracts $n$-point functions:

    $$\langle O(x_1)\cdots O(x_n)\rangle =
    \frac{\delta^n \log Z_\text{CFT}}{\delta\phi_0(x_1)\cdots\delta\phi_0(x_n)}
    \Biggr|_{\phi_0\,=\,0} \tag{8}$$

    \textbf{The GKPW Dictionary}

    The precise identification — written down by Gubser, Klebanov, Polyakov and
    independently by Witten in 1998 — equates the two partition functions when
    the bulk field is held to the boundary value $\phi_0$:

    $$Z_\text{CFT}[\phi_0] =
    Z_\text{string}\!\left[\left.\phi\right|_{z\to 0} = \phi_0\right] \tag{9}$$

    In the classical gravity limit (large $N$, large $\lambda$):

    $$\left\langle\exp\!\left(\int\phi_0\,O\right)\right\rangle_{\!\text{CFT}}
    = e^{-S_\text{on-shell}[\phi_0]} \tag{10}$$

    The two-point function follows from the bulk-to-boundary propagator:

    $$\langle O(x)\,O(x')\rangle = \frac{C_\Delta}{|x - x'|^{2\Delta}} \tag{11}$$

    This is exactly the form required by conformal invariance.

    \textbf{The Parameter Dictionary}

    The mapping in the canonical example — Type IIB string theory on
    $\text{AdS}_5 \times S^5$ dual to $\mathcal{N} = 4$ Super Yang-Mills with
    gauge group $SU(N)$:

    \center{\table[width:70, frame:single, pad:{l:1,r:1}]{
        \row[frame:{b:double}]{
            \col[width:37, align:c]{Gravity side}
            \col[align:c]{CFT side}
        }
        \row[frame:{b:single}]{
            \col{AdS radius $L$ / string length $\ell_s$}
            \col{'t Hooft coupling $\lambda = g_{YM}^2 N$}
        }
        \row{
            \col{Newton's constant $G_N$}
            \col{Rank of gauge group $N$}
        }
        \row{
            \col{String coupling $g_s$}
            \col{$g_{YM}^2$}
        }
        \row{
            \col{Bulk mass $m^2 L^2$}
            \col{Conformal dimension $\Delta(\Delta - d)$}
        }
        \row{
            \col{Bulk field $\phi$}
            \col{CFT operator $O$}
        }
        \row{
            \col{Black hole in bulk}
            \col{Thermal state in CFT}
        }
    }}

    $$\frac{L^4}{\ell_s^4} = \lambda = g_{YM}^2 N \qquad
    \frac{L^8}{G_N} \sim N^2 \tag{12}$$

    This reveals why direct verification is hard: the gravity approximation is
    valid when $\lambda \gg 1$, but perturbative field theory requires $\lambda
    \ll 1$. The two tractable regimes do not overlap.

    \textbf{Ryu-Takayanagi: Geometry from Entanglement}

    For a region $A$ on the boundary, the entanglement entropy of the CFT vacuum
    state is:

    $$S_A = \frac{\text{Area}(\gamma_A)}{4G_N} \tag{RT}$$

    where $\gamma_A$ is the \textbf{minimal area surface} in the bulk homologous
    to $A$ and anchored to $\partial A$ on the boundary. This directly
    generalises the Bekenstein-Hawking formula to arbitrary regions — not just
    black holes — suggesting that the entanglement structure of the CFT literally
    \textit{encodes} the geometry of the bulk spacetime.

    \textbf{What Makes It Deep}

    The bulk radial coordinate $z$ maps to the renormalization group scale on the
    boundary. Physics deep in the bulk ($z \to \infty$) encodes infrared physics
    in the CFT; physics near the boundary ($z \to 0$) encodes ultraviolet
    behaviour. Geometry of spacetime is, in this sense, a picture of the RG flow
    of a quantum field theory. An extra dimension of space emerges from the
    structure of quantum entanglement and renormalization.
@end

